## State Management

### Pinia Store Structure

```typescript
// ✅ Store structure example
import { defineStore } from 'pinia'
import type { Character } from '@/types'

export const useCharacterStore = defineStore('character', () => {
	// State
	const characters = ref<Character[]>([])
	const currentCharacter = ref<Character | null>(null)
	const isLoading = ref(false)
	const error = ref<string | null>(null)

	// Getters
	const characterCount = computed(() => characters.value.length)
	const hasCurrentCharacter = computed(() => currentCharacter.value !== null)

	// Actions
	async function loadCharacter(id: number) {
		isLoading.value = true
		error.value = null

		try {
			const character = await characterService.getCharacter(id)
			currentCharacter.value = character
		} catch (err) {
			error.value = err instanceof Error ? err.message : 'Unknown error'
		} finally {
			isLoading.value = false
		}
	}

	return {
		// State
		characters: readonly(characters),
		currentCharacter: readonly(currentCharacter),
		isLoading: readonly(isLoading),
		error: readonly(error),

		// Getters
		characterCount,
		hasCurrentCharacter,

		// Actions
		loadCharacter
	}
})
```

### State Updates

```typescript
// ✅ Immutable updates
const updateCharacterName = (id: number, name: string) => {
	const index = characters.value.findIndex(c => c.id === id)
	if (index !== -1) {
		characters.value[index] = {
			...characters.value[index],
			name
		}
	}
}

// ✅ Use helper functions for complex updates
const mergeCharacterData = (character: Character, updates: Partial<Character>) => {
	return {
		...character,
		...updates,
		_modules: {
			...character._modules,
			...updates._modules
		}
	}
}
```

## Internationalization (i18n)

### Custom Translation Workflow

FATE: Core uses a custom translation workflow. **AI agents should ONLY add new translation keys to `scripts/localizer/newTranslationKeys.json` with English values**. The human developer will handle the rest of the translation process.

#### Adding New Translation Keys

```json
// ✅ Add new keys to scripts/localizer/newTranslationKeys.json
{
	"character": {
		"creation": {
			"step1": "Basic Information",
			"step2": "Module Selection",
			"title": "Create New Character"
		},
		"name": "Character Name"
	},
	"modules": {
		"newFeature": {
			"description": {
				"full": "Comprehensive description of what this feature does",
				"short": "Brief description of the new feature"
			},
			"name": "New Feature"
		}
	}
}
```

#### Translation Key Structure

- Use **hierarchical dot notation** for logical grouping
- Provide **clear, descriptive English text** as values
- Group related keys under common namespaces
- Use consistent naming patterns across the application

#### Translation Workflow Steps

1. **AI Agent**: Add new translation keys with English values to `scripts/localizer/newTranslationKeys.json`
2. **Human Developer**: Send keys to translation provider
3. **Translation Provider**: Return translated object with all supported languages
4. **Human Developer**: Process translations using the localizer script (`pnpm translate`)

### Translation Usage in Code

```vue
<template>
	<!-- ✅ Simple translations -->
	<h1>{{ $t('character.name') }}</h1>

	<!-- ✅ Interpolation -->
	<p>{{ $t('character.level', { level: character.level }) }}</p>

	<!-- ✅ Pluralization -->
	<span>{{ $tc('character.items', itemCount, { count: itemCount }) }}</span>
</template>
```

### Module Translations

For modules, add translation keys to the module-specific section in `newTranslationKeys.json`:

```json
// ✅ Module-specific translation keys
{
	"modules": {
		"author@module-name": {
			"actions": {
				"cancel": "Cancel",
				"delete": "Delete Item",
				"save": "Save Changes"
			},
			"description": {
				"full": "Detailed explanation of module functionality",
				"short": "Brief module description"
			},
			"fields": {
				"anotherField": "Another Field Label",
				"fieldName": "Field Label"
			},
			"name": "Module Display Name"
		}
	}
}
```

